 economic and political development of Asturias-León from the Islamic conquest to 1031. Using a forensic comparative method, which examinesthe abundant charter material from two regions of northern Spain - the Liébana valley in Cantabria, and the Celanova region of southern Galicia - it sheds new light on village society, the workings of government, and the constantswirl of buying, selling and donating that marked the rhythms of daily life. It also maps the contact points between rulers and ruled, offering new insights on the motivations and actions of both peasant proprietors and aristocrats. Robert Portass is Senior Lecturer in Medieval History at the University of Lincoln.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLiâebana Region (Spain)--Politics and government--711-1516. 4aHispanic Studies. 4aIslamic Studies. 4aMedieval History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAristocracy.  aEarly Medieval Spain.  aEighth century.  aEuropean history.  aGalicia.  aIberian Peninsula.  aMedieval Christianity.  aMedieval History.  aMedieval Islam.  aMedieval Village.  aPeasantry.  aSocial history.  aSpanish history.  aStraits of Gibraltar.  aTariq ibn Ziyad.1 aPortass, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311143130740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178744003640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787440036423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787440036/original  a978-3-11-143130-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles